08304nam a2201945Ia 9780691188980DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911889807 a10.1515/97806911889802doi  a(DE-B1597)528262  a(OCoLC)1082518952  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aGV880.22 7aSPO0030402bisacsh04a796.3572231 aPhillips, Christopher J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScouting and Scoring :bHow We Know What We Know about Baseball /cChristopher J. Phillips. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b15 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Bases of Data -- t2. Henry Chadwick and Scoring Technology -- t3. Official Scoring -- t4. From Project Scoresheet to Big Data -- t5. The Practice of Pricing the Body -- t6. Measuring Head and Heart -- t7. A Machine for Objectivity -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations Used in Notes -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn in-depth look at the intersection of judgment and statistics in baseballScouting and scoring are considered fundamentally different ways of ascertaining value in baseball. Scouting seems to rely on experience and intuition, scoring on performance metrics and statistics. In Scouting and Scoring, Christopher Phillips rejects these simplistic divisions. He shows how both scouts and scorers rely on numbers, bureaucracy, trust, and human labor in order to make sound judgments about the value of baseball players.Tracing baseball’s story from the nineteenth century to today, Phillips explains that the sport was one of the earliest and most consequential fields for the introduction of numerical analysis. New technologies and methods of data collection were supposed to enable teams to quantify the drafting and managing of players—replacing scouting with scoring. But that’s not how things turned out. Over the decades, scouting and scoring started looking increasingly similar. Scouts expressed their judgments in highly formulaic ways, using numerical grades and scientific instruments to evaluate players. Scorers drew on moral judgments, depended on human labor to maintain and correct data, and designed bureaucratic systems to make statistics appear reliable. From the invention of official scorers and Statcast to the creation of the Major League Scouting Bureau, the history of baseball reveals the inextricable connections between human expertise and data science.A unique consideration of the role of quantitative measurement and human judgment, Scouting and Scoring provides an entirely fresh understanding of baseball by showing what the sport reveals about reliable knowledge in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBaseballxScouting. 0aBaseball-Scouting-United States. 0aSports officiating. 0aSports-United States-Statistics. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Baseball / Statistics.2bisacsh  aAccounting.  aAdobe.  aAdolphe Quetelet.  aAnnals (Tacitus).  aArbitration.  aArithmetic.  aAward.  aBatting order (cricket).  aBig data.  aBiomedical sciences.  aBook.  aBoosterism.  aBruno Latour.  aBureaucrat.  aBusiness manager.  aCD-ROM.  aCalculation.  aCambridge University Press.  aCareer.  aCash Bonus.  aCompetition.  aComputer memory.  aComputer.  aControl Data Corporation.  aCredential.  aCredibility.  aData analysis.  aData science.  aData.  aDatabase.  aDavid Edgerton (historian).  aDe facto standard.  aDemerit.  aDetermination.  aDot-com bubble.  aEmeritus.  aFile system.  aGallatin S